s, LaFollette focuses on the fragile "peer review" process—the editorial system of seeking pre-publication opinions from experts. She addresses the cultural glorification of science, which, combined with a scientist's thirst for achievement, can seem to make cheating worth the danger. She describes the great risks taken by the accusers—often scholars of less prestige and power than the accused—whom she calls "nemesis figures" for their relentless dedication to uncovering dishonesty.In sober warning, LaFollette notes that impatient calls from Congress, journalists, and taxpayers for greater accountability from scientists have important implications for the entire system of scientific research and communication.Provocative and learned, Stealing Into Print is certain to become the authoritative work on scientific fraud, invaluable to the scientific community, policy makers, and the general public.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAuthorshipxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aAuthorship. 0aFraud in science. 0aFraud. 0aPlagiarism. 0aProfessional ethics. 0aPublishers and publishingxProfessional ethics. 0aResearch. 0aScience publishingxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aScientistsxProfessional ethics. 0aTechnical writingxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aWriting. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aaccountability.  aauthorship.  acheating.  acongress.  acultural glorification of science.  adishonesty.  aethics.  aexposure.  afabricating data.  afalse data.  afraud.  afraudulent.  agovernment.  amedia studies.  amisconduct.  amorality.  anemesis figures.  apeer review process.  aplagiarism.  apre publication opinions.  apsychology.  apublication.  aretraction.  ascandal.  ascience.  ascientific communication.  ascientific community.  ascientific journals.  ascient